name: Pork and Scallion Dumplings With Crispy Skirt

steps.instruction:
### Steps
1. Place 8 oz. ground pork (not lean) in a medium bowl
2. Trim roots and 1" from tops of 8 scallions; discard
3. Thinly slice; transfer 2 Tbsp. scallion to a small bowl and set aside for dipping sauce
4. Coarsely chop remaining scallions and add to bowl with pork
5. Peel 1" piece ginger with a spoon and finely grate into bowl with pork using a Microplane
6. Add 2 tsp. soy sauce,  tsp. kosher salt, and  tsp. freshly ground white or black pepper to pork
7. Rake through pork with chopsticks or your hands to quickly but thoroughly combine ingredients
8. Get ready to form the dumplings: Place twenty-four 3"-diameter wonton wrappers on a work surface and cover with a damp kitchen towel to prevent them from drying out
9. Place a small bowl of water nearby
10. Place 1 wrapper in the palm of your nondominant hand
11. Scoop out a rounded teaspoonful of filling and place into center of wrapper
12. Use teaspoon to nudge filling into a football shape (This will make it easier to fold the wrapper around it.)
![](https://assets.bonappetit.com/photos/5eb5cbc31a6c44e89f09ba75/master/w_1024/Basically-Dumpling-Process-02.jpg)
13. Dip a finger on your dominant hand in water and lightly moisten the half of the wrapper that is closest to you
14. Using your dominant hand, fold wrapper in half over filling and pinch closed using both of your hands
15. Using your fingers, make 67 pleats along the edge, pressing each pleat closed after you form it
16. To make the slurry for your crispy skirt, whisk 3 Tbsp. unseasoned rice vinegar, 4 tsp. all-purpose flour, 4 tsp. cornstarch, remaining  tsp. kosher salt, and 2 cups water in a large measuring glass to combine
17. Now you are ready to cook your dumplings. Heat 2 tsp. vegetable oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high
18. Arrange 610 dumplings in pan (steam fewer at a time if you want a more crispy skirt) and cook until they start to sizzle, about 1 minute (You dont want them to take on any color at this point.)
19. Stir slurry well and add a generous  cup to pan
20. Cover and steam dumplings 5 minutes
21. Remove lid. Dumplings should be plumped and cooked through and most of the water should have evaporated, leaving a thin lacy layer of slurry beneath them
22. Cover and cook a minute longer if needed
23. Uncover dumplings and cook until all the liquid evaporates from slurry and it becomes a crisp, golden brown skirt, about 2 minutes
    - You may need to rotate your pan as some areas will brown faster than others
![](https://assets.bonappetit.com/photos/5eb5cbc40c15fbb604578e52/master/w_1024/Basically-Dumpling-Process-03.jpg)
24. Invert a plate over pan and flip dumplings out onto plate (You can also slide them out onto a plate if thats more your comfort level.
25. Repeat cooking process with remaining dumplings and slurry (stirring well before each batch) in 23 more batches, adding 2 tsp. vegetable oil to pan after each batch.
26. While the dumplings are cooking, make the dipping sauce. Add 2 tsp. chili oil (if using), remaining 2 Tbsp. unseasoned rice vinegar, and remaining 2 Tbsp. soy sauce to reserved sliced scallions and mix well
